Hot take: You donâ€™t need to sign up for a race to run a marathon. 

4 years ago today I went out for my daily run. Nice and easy. I donâ€™t know what it was about the day but I just felt like I could keep going. So I kept on running. 8 miles. 10 miles. Half marathon. 15 miles. 18 miles. 20 miles. Could I do it? Could I keep going? 24 miles. Could I close a marathon?? 

26.26 miles later I ran my first full marathon. On my own. No plan. No route. No support. No crowd. No cheers. No finish line. Just miles and milestones. 

Running is personal. Anyone can sign up for a race. Not anyone wakes up, rolls out of bed, and just decides to run a solo marathon. Regardless of anyone else, I didnâ€™t think I could do it. Not too long ago I couldnâ€™t run a mile. The audacity to think I could run a marathon for the hell of it. But I did. I went the distance. I surprised myself. 

I learned a lot in a moments time. 4 hours of nothing but me and the road. 

Yeah marathons are cool. Organized races are an experience. But solo running is something else. It taught me you donâ€™t need to sign up for a race to run a marathon. You donâ€™t need to win a lottery to feel special. Youâ€™re not missing out if you donâ€™t run a major. I learned if you take away the glam and look at running in its purity, youâ€™re really look at a mirror. 

Whether thereâ€™s a crowd or not. Whether thereâ€™s a finish line or not. 26.2 miles is 26.2 miles.

Run your own race.

Here's a fun edit I did of footage from @noriyaro on the famous Japanese "Dajiban" racing.
Arguably Alex was THE guy to really record and introduce westerners to the crazy love and culture of the Dodge Tradesman in Japanese motorsports many years ago via his YouTube channel and journalist work.
I, being a fan of Malaise Era V8 boats, stock car racing, and vans, naturally took fascination with this cult.
The Dajiban from my understanding spawned from racing teams using their vans to race on off-time. That then spiraled into a full blown racing league.
I'd absolutely love to build a van here in the states with some ridiculous N/A Mopar V8 and manual swap.
